review_blob: The first taste felt really sweet, but everything after that was just marvelous. I thoroughly enjoyed this beer. Aroma is sweet and yeasty, and the flavor is nice and hoppy with a lot of pleasant belgian yeastiness. This does a nice job of balancing belgian trippel and ipa without letting either one really take over.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob:
Pours dark brown with zero head. Smells like brandy and dark chocolate. Thick syrupy bite to the nose.

Flavor is buttery smooth chocolate brandy goodness. A bit like really really really good black licorice. Im also getting a bit of a dark chocolate godiva liquor going. Some chocolate orange vibes too. Wild!

One thing you take away from this is that this is so stinking smooth, with a warming from the alcohol too. Beer is mostly flat, by design I believe.

Wow, this is wild. Very yummy!

Feels much like a red wine, dry, but with a wood-like, apple-sour vibe to it. Really drinkable and rather tasty all-around. Goes surprisingly well with some nice strong licorice. Its approachable, but I think only if youre into this sort of funky beer (which I am!)
beer_name: New Belgium Lips of Faith - Dark Kriek

review_blob: This is quite nice. Very smooth and rich. I recall some vanilla and bourbon, but also with all the good stuff I enjoy from the regular arrogant bastard. Im glad they made this.
I really wanted to like this one, but in the end, it felt thin and not all that hoppy. I like the idea, in fact Ive even brewed one of these myself, but I just couldnt get into it.

A canonical brown. Looks fantastic. Aroma is nutty, hint of roast, and some good malt. Flavor is just excellent, nice malt with some good hop hints. Finish is clean and good. You cant go wrong with this brown. Averys kinda known for their huge beers, but this is one of their best, methinks.
This has become a favorite of mine lately. Love the rich chocolate aroma backed by spice hops. Flavor is the same with just a hint of sour and smokiness. I order this regularly at my favorite pub.

I liked this beer quite a bit more than I thought I would. (No idea actually why I thought I wouldnt like it). Anyway, it was pretty delicious! Pours caramel amber with a medium body. Aroma is malty, grainy, nutty and pleasant. Flavor is much of the same, with a mild hoppiness. The whole beer is much richer than I anticipated. I eagerly refilled my glass.

I remember distinctly the first time I tried this beer. It was circa 2003 in Haines, Alaska. I hadnt ever really had anything this crazy before. The copy on the bottle is hilarious, with the cap telling me Im not worthy. Am I? Whew, I hope so. Flavor is mighty, lots of hops, citrus, dates, fresh fruit. Finish isnt too cloying, if youre determined, you can make it through a bomber in an evening. Just dont plan on driving.

Super delicious. At first sip I knew Id want more. Maybe even some to take home. Pours black w/ tan head. Aroma is roasty,and nutty. Flavor is dark and sweet, with some roastiness and hops to balance the sweetness. Finish is pleasant. Makes you want more. Yum.

Despite being from Anheuser-Busch this isnt a bad beer at all. A nice answer to Blue Moon, which I believe is still superior. Aroma is citrus with a hint of yeast and grain. Flavor is a little thin, but not bad. Overall a decent wit nothing too daring. Pretty drinkable.

Pours amber, with lots of malt, apple and caramel on the aroma. Flavor is mild, sweet, and caramel. Hops are only mildly apparent in just a hint of grapefruit and maybe a bit of earthiness. Very drinkable, and since its an altbier, a bit of a change of pace from most ambers.
Citrus and sour abound, with some nice orange peel and coriander. I dig this beer. This feels as good as it tastes.

Aroma is sweeeet, with lots of caramel and bourbon. The pour is black with a fairly quick dissipating brown head. Flavor is like sweet chocolate. Maybe some candied plums and dark toast and smoke. Alcohol is pretty well disguised behind this tasty complex flavor. The aroma continues to please throughout the enjoyment of this beer. Eventually you *definitely* start to notice the alcohol. Finish is pleasant, some residual carbon and just a hint of stickiness on the sides of the tongue.

Pleasant lager vibe with some resinous aroma. Flavor has some decent malt and grain to it, with more of the somewhat noticeable hops as well. Id order it again. I had this from a can, so zero skunkage.

Thick oily black. Very tasty looking. Aroma is malty, chocolate, rich fruits. Flavor is very reminicent of rich creamy espresso and dark dark chocolate. This is a good one to be patient with and let evolve as it warms up in your glass. The finish is somewhat like burnt bacon. Yum!
beer_name: Stone 20th Anniversary Encore Series: Bitter Chocolate Oatmeal Stout

review_blob: This is one to try a few times, thats for sure. I fully enjoyed my first bottle, though I think I did expect the whole thing to be a bit beefier - more a testament to my expectations than anything. Aroma is total bret that makes it feel rather peachy. Flavors are jammy, peachy, and a hint of spice. I expected the fig to show though a bit more, but it still was good. My wife loved it. I think Ill get a few more, one to try super cold, and a few to let sit for a year or two to see what happens.
This is a new favorite IPA for me. Total hop bomb of some of my favorite hops, backed by some nice malt to make a classic IPA.

I really enjoyed this very complex IPA. Ha a full gamut of delicious hops, from a pine resin flavor over to a spice and fruit vibe as well. All well-balanced by some pleasant malt backbone. 7% alcohol was nicely veiled by the flavors but still noticeable. Id gladly order this again and again.

Tawny colored w/ tan head. Aroma is pretty sweet, some toast and hint of spice hops. Flavor is very sweet, followed by alcohol and again a hint of spice hops. Doesnt taste like an ESB to me, but I suppose thats what they were going for. Not entirely sure Id buy another 6 pack of this, but it was a fun experiment.

2007 Vintage. Pours a reddish brown color w/ a creamy head. Aroma is really nice - sweet, with some cantaloupe and a bit of toasty malt. Flavor is malt-forward with some metallic tones. Very dry, lots of spice coming through, including some yummy black pepper. Some noticeable red wine vibes. Not at all the palate you would expect from the aroma, but its still mighty enjoyable.
A good Pils. Not super innovative or anything, but far better than pretty much any other widely available mexican lagers. Id be happy to pick up another. Solid.

This was interesting and Im glad I tried it. The grape sweetness was definitely more prominent than any hoppiness one would imagine with the "pale ale" in the title. This is deifnitely a fruit beer first. The maple was a nice addition as well. I rarely meet a fruit beer that I do enjoy and this is one of them. Well done Lili!
beer_name: Samuel Adams LongShot Grape Pale Ale

review_blob: Wowie. This was a huge hit. Aroma is super malty with some nice toast to it. Flavor is like a toasted chocolate covered banana. I even got some ice cream to drizzle this over and it was just marvelous. My wife enjoyed it very much as well. Well done Rodney!
Lots of resin, spice and citrus all mixed into one mighty IPA. Attractive, bold, and a bit mischievous. Definitely a crowdpleaser for the hop nuts.

Pale golden color with ample white head made up of medium-sized bubbles. Aroma is sweet, grainy and some orange. Flavor is mild, malty and some more orange with a grapefruit and caramel aftertaste. Eventually some spice character comes out, with some pepper flavors on the back of the tongue. Body is medium to light with lots of carbonation. Im no expert on Klsch style beers, but this seems to fit the deScription fairly well. Id say this errs on teh side of the malts though, since I dont see the hops being very prominent, and it feels like the taste doesnt back up the aroma as much as Id like. All in all though its tasty. VERY glad to see Alaskan Beers finally make it to Colorado.

Gorgeous aroma - lots of cascade and some pale maltiness too. Appearance-wise its very attractive. Light copper with a bountiful white head. I enjoy the taste quite a bit - more spiciness than i anticipated (not a bad thing at all). Body is lighter than expected too - making for a pretty easy drinking pale. Very pleasant all around and Im really really excited that NB is making this! (fwiw, Ive met arrow a few years ago, such a sweet dog).

Pours nice and dark with a moderate tan head, but the aroma tells you theres more going on here. Its sweet and tangy, with some nice roastiness. Flavor is heavy on the bourbon, and the roast balances really nicely. Moderate to heavy body that feels appropriate given the style and bourbon aspect. Id recommend this to anybody looking for something interesting in the stout range.

Pours a dark red mahogany with a light tan head. Very minimal lacing. Aroma is toasty, hint of alcohol and plum. No spice or hops. Flavor is warm and toasty. Hop presence is all but absent. Only a hint of spice and citrus. Malt is dominant, with lots of coffee and cola vibes. Light bodied, mild cloying on the finish. Feels appropriate to a light bodied porter like this. Very enjoyable and drinkable porter. Much thanks to Doppelganger for sending this one my way.

Pours a marvelous light copper w/ a white htead. Aroma is crisp, spicy. Flavor is a spicy flavor with an excellent malt backbone.  Very crisp and clean, with a mineral, salty taste. I love the finish - very clean and leaves a metallic dry mouthfeel. Overall its an excellent example of a really interesting, delicious lager. Cant thank Doppelganger enough for sending this one my way.

My five-word review would be "a decent solid pale ale". Its fairly balanced with a nice multi-dimensional hop aroma and flavor. Some citrus, grass, spice balanced by a basic malt backbone. I like it - especially after it warms up a tad. Id buy it again.

Clean fairly fresh aroma, not really hoppy but more interesting than most "premium lager". Flavor is somewhat grainy and a hint of earthy hops. Finish is more of the same. Very clean. I was gifted a 6 pack of this and Im already halfway through. I think its underrated here, but lets not be mistaken, its nothing mindblowing.

Pours a nice hazy amber/copper with a moderate tan head. Aroma is rich and creamy, with lots of malt, not a ton else going on except for some noticeable alcohol. Flavor is more richness and caramel with some spice on the back-end. This is pretty tasty but Id like some more dimension to it.

Aroma is fantastic - a nice balanced malty & hoppy aroma. Smells fresh (like some of my fermenters when Im brewing - THAT fresh), with some hints of spices like mint and nutmeg. Pours a nice amber with a white head that lasts. Flavor isnt quite as radical, but its still nice. This is a very easy drinking, approachable, balanced winter ale.

Amber colored with a generous head. Comes across really malty, not a lot of hops in the nose or flavor. I used to drink this alot years ago, but generally not all that excited about it now that Ive had so many more interesting beers. Still, pretty drinkable and I wouldnt turn one down. I wouldnt dare call this a porter though. Whats up with that?

Pours mahogany with ample tan head. Aroma is roast, apples, some spice with hints of alcohol. Flavor is a nice balanced strong flavor. Citrus hops, some oak, roastiness, more apples and plum. Nice hop and roast flavor on the finish. This is really drinkable. The alcohol lends minimal heat - but be careful - its there alright! Good stuff!
beer_name: Stone Sublimely Self Righteous Black IPA

review_blob: Gorgeous golden clear pour with a giant white head. Aroma is noticeably hoppy, with some grass, grain and a general crispiness. Flavor is really rich, I taste lots of citrus, some spice and lots of sweetness that I hadnt anticipated. The finish is really clean with a bit of bitterness. I dig it. Really drinkable and full of surprises.

Pours mahogany with a great looking tan head. Aroma is caramel, malt, hint of toastiness, plum and mild spiciness. Flavor is sweet, decent amount of fruits and malt, giving way to more hints of bitter and spice. Its pretty well balanced for a winter ale. Its not crazy, radical or shocking. Its just a great winter ale. Id definitely purchase this again.

Clear light copper color with a decent cream head. Aroma is strong spicy and resinous hop with a crystal malt noticeable as well. Flavor is more of the same - delivering on the aroma expectations nicely. Distinct piney finish. I like chinook so I enjoy this beer, but in large quantities it would definitely be too much of a good thing. I wouldnt hand this to someone who hasnt really gotten into IPAs much, but Id give it to someone who I know likes the northwest hops, or just someone who wants to try a new take on an IPA.

aroma is slightly roasty and nutty. Small hints of the spiciness. Flavor is chocolaty, slightly acidic, and hints of cold coffee. This makes for a great porter. The chocolate gives it some nice roastiness that I really enjoy. Very drinkable.

Aroma is nice and spicy with some decent caramel too. Im getting clove and pine with some dustiness - like fall. Flavor is piney, bitter, like walking through the woods. Palate is moderate to light, finish is clean with some of that hop bitterness. Well done. Not what youd expect from a seasonal winter, but on the other hand, this is a great take on that style. Using the noble hops for spices is a fun idea.

Pours amber, with a great foamy head. Aroma is very floral, hint of toasty, spicy. Lots of orange and coriander, maybe some nutmeg. Flavor is excellent, very much delivering on every bit of the aroma. A most delicious, very fabulous example of the style.

Pours light golden with an amazing head. Very lovely. Aroma is yeasty - kinda light floral with some spicy graininess. Flavor is sweet, yeasty and some good hints of spiciness. All in all its approachable and pleasant. A good belgian golden.

Pale yellow with a white head. Smells grainy with a hint of spicy hops, but not much going on there. Flavor is pretty predictable - grainy, small hints of spice and thats pretty much it. Not very exciting, pretty decent I suppose for a pale lager.

INKY black with a ton of creamy brown head. Aroma is chocolate dominant with hints of alcohol. Flavor is coffee and super dark cocoa chocolate. Lots of roast flavor, hints of carbon, and oak. For an oatmeal stout Id expect a bit more creaminess in the mouthfeel, but despite that this is a really enjoyable stout. I really like it.

Pours nice and golden - with a hint of amber. Plenty of a creamy head as well. Flavor is sweet, with orange and caramel. Not super hoppy, but I suppose thats not the point with this beer. I would have liked to experience some more toasty flavors though.
Pours like an IPA. Smells like honey, malt and sour. Flavor delivers with much of the same. All in all, I enjoy a more tart lambic, as this doesnt seem super adventurous.

This is a pretty much perfect version of a scotch ale. Lots of malt, that toasty roasty aroma and flavor... its just really well done. Im really enjoying all the malt - lots of fruit - plum, apple, maybe some licorice... this whole toasty smoke overtone is really working well. The alcohol is barely noticeable in the flavor. Its really smooth. All in all Im impressed.

This is a canonical irish ale. The aroma is nice and malty, with some metallic toasted vibes. The flavor delivers well with the same malty, metallic toasted flavors. It looks great and feels great on the tongue.

Pours amber with a tannish cream head. Lots of apple in the aroma. That gives way to alcohol, belgian yeast and malt. Flavor is initially just kinda malty, over time I get some more apple, yeast, and some more complex malty vibes with some metallic hints too. Im struck by how moderate to thin the body is. For a 9.5%, I expected this to feel bigger. This is deceptively small-feeling. Pretty remarkable, really! All in all, not really what I look for in a Belgian strong. Id like more spiciness and a more caramel feel to it, but I still really enjoy this beer. Id consider giving it as a gift to an inexperienced drinker to introduce them to the world of belgians.
